\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Book Five\uc0\u8232 \'a0Diomedes Goes to Battle\
\'a0 \'97[Athena inspires Diomedes with special powers; Athena takes Ares from the battle; Achaean leaders kill many Trojans; Diomedes' special glory on the field; Pandarus hits Diomedes with an arrow; Athena restores Diomedes, who continues his battle frenzy; Aeneas and Pandarus move out against Diomedes; Diomedeskills Pandarus, wounds Aeneas; Aphrodite saves Aeneas; Sthenelus captures Aeneas' horses; Diomedes attacks and wounds Aphrodite, who returns to Olympus;Diomedes threatens Apollo; Apollo heals Aeneas; Sarpedon complains to Hector; the battle continues; Sarpedon kills Tlepolemus, but is wounded; Athena and Hera go down to the battlefield; Athena and Diomedes attack and wound Ares; Ares returns to Olympus]\
Then Pallas Athena gave Diomedes, son of Tydeus,\uc0\u8232 strength and courage, so among all Argives,\u8232 he\'92d stand out and win heroic glory.\u8232 She made his helmet blaze with tireless flames,\u8232 his shield as well\'97like a late star in summer\u8232 which shines especially bright, newly risen from its bath\u8232 in Ocean\'92s streams. Around his head and shoulders\u8232 the goddess put a fiery glow, then drove him forward,\u8232 right into the middle of the strife, the killing zone,\u8232 where most warriors fight.Among the Trojans\u8232 was a rich and honourable man called Dares,\u8232 priest of Hephaestus. He had two sons\'97Phegeus  \'97[10]\u8232 and Idaios\'97both very skilled in all aspects of war.\u8232 Moving forward in their chariot to the front,\u8232 these two charged Diomedes, who was on foot,\u8232 staying on the ground. When they were at close range,\u8232 Phegeus was the first to hurl his long-shadowed spear.\u8232 The spear point flew by Diomedes\'92 left shoulder\'97\u8232 it missed him. Tydeus\'92 son then threw his spear.\u8232 The weapon did not leave his hand and miss the target.\u8232 It hit Phegeus right between the nipples\u8232 and knocked him from his splendid chariot.\u8232 Idaios jumped out and ran off from his horses. \'97[20]\u8232 He didn\'92t dare protect his slaughtered brother\'92s corpse.\u8232 Even so, he wouldn\'92t have escaped black doom,\u8232 but Hephaestus saved him with a dark cloud cover,\u8232 so his aged father wouldn\'92t waste away with grief.\u8232 Tydeus\'92 son, great Diomedes, drove the horses off,\u8232 then gave them to his comrades to take back to the ships.\u8232 When great-hearted Trojans saw those two sons of Dares\'97one shunning battle, one dead beside his chariot\'97\u8232 all their hearts were stirred.\'a0\'a0Then Athena, eyes glittering,\u8232 took her brother, headstrong Ares, by the hand,  \'97[30]\u8232 and said to him:\
\'93Ares, Ares, insatiable man-killer,\uc0\u8232 destroyer of cities, why don\'92t we leave\u8232 Trojans and Achaeans to fight it out?\u8232 Father Zeus will make one group victorious.\u8232 Let\'92s withdraw, avoiding Zeus\'92 anger.\'94\
With these words, she led headstrong Ares from the battle,\uc0\u8232 then sat him down by Scamander river bank.Danaans then began to push the Trojans back.\u8232 Each leader killed his enemy. First, Agamemnon,\u8232 king of men, threw huge Odius, chief of the Halizoni,\u8232 from his chariot. His spear first struck him in the back,  \'97[40]\u8232 between the shoulder blades, as he turned to flee.\u8232 It drove clean through his chest. Odius pitched forward\u8232 with a thud, his armour rattling round him as he fell.\u8232 Idomeneus slaughtered Phaestus, son of Borus,\u8232 a Meonian, who\'92d come from fertile Tarne.\u8232 With his long spear, skilful Idomeneus struck him\u8232 in his right shoulder, as he climbed in his chariot.\u8232 Dreadful darkness came and gathered Phaestus in.\u8232 Those attending Idomeneus stripped the armour.\u8232 Then with his sharp spear Menelaus, son of Atreus,\u8232 killed Scamandrius, son of Strophius, a huntsman.  \'97[50]\u8232 Artemis herself had taught him how to shoot\u8232 every animal raised in the mountain forests.\u8232 But archer Artemis was no help to him then,\u8232 no more than was his expertise in archery,\u8232 at which he\'92d been pre-eminent in former times.\'a0\u8232 For fine spearman Menelaus, son of Atreus,\u8232 caught him as he ran away in front of him,\u8232 hitting him in the back between his shoulder blades,\u8232 forcing the spear right through Scamandrius\'92 chest.\u8232 He fell head first. His armour rattled round him.\
Meriones then killed Phereclus, son of Tecton,\uc0\u8232 Harmon\'92s son, whose hands could make fine objects of all sorts. \'97[60]\u8232 Pallas Athena had a special love for him.\u8232 He was the one who\'92d made well-balanced ships\u8232 for Paris at the start of all the trouble,\'a0\u8232 bringing disaster on the Trojans and on Paris, too,\u8232 for he was ignorant of what gods had decreed.\u8232 Meriones went after Phereclus as he ran off,\u8232 hurled his spear straight into his right buttock.\u8232 The spear point pushed on through, below the bone,\u8232 piercing his bladder. He fell down on his knees,\u8232 screaming. Then death carried him into its shadows.\
Then Meges killed Pedaeus, Antenor\'92s bastard son.\uc0\u8232 Theano had raised him with all care, loving him \'97[70]\u8232 as one of her own children, to please her husband.That famous spearman Meges, son of Phyleus,\u8232 coming up close, drove a sharp spear in his neck,\u8232 into the nape behind his head. The bronze point,\u8232 slicing under his tongue, smashed through his teeth.\u8232 He fell into the dust, jaws locked on the cold bronze.\
Eurypylus, Euaemon\'92s son, killed lord Hypsenor,\uc0\u8232 son of proud Dolopion, Scamander\'92s priest,\u8232 a man honoured by his people as a god.\u8232 Eurypylus, Euaemon\'92s splendid son, caught him\u8232 as he ran off in front of him. Going quickly after him, \'97[80]\u8232 Eurypylus struck at Hypsenor\'92s shoulder\'97\u8232 his sharp sword sliced off Hypsenor\'92s brawny arm.\u8232 The bloody limb fell on the ground. Then death\'92s black night,\u8232 all-powerful fate, moved in and stole away his sight.\
Thus these men kept toiling in the battle frenzy.\uc0\u8232 As for Diomedes, you couldn\'92t tell where he belonged,\u8232 whether among the Trojans or Achaeans.\u8232 For he rushed across the plain like a swollen river,\u8232 like a swift winter torrent bursting dikes\'97\u8232 no dam put in its wway can hold it back,no barrier of fruitful vineyards check its current,  \'97[90]\u8232 as all at once it floods when storms from Zeus roar down.\u8232 It knocks aside all fine things built by farmers,\u8232 hard-working men. That\'92s how the son of Tydeus\u8232 drove the dense ranks of Trojans into mass confusion.\u8232 For all their numbers they could not contain him.\
Lycaon\'92s fine son saw Diomedes moving fast\uc0\u8232 along the plain, pushing Trojan ranks in front of him,\u8232 in complete disorder. He quickly bent his bow,\u8232 taking aim at Diomedes. He shot an arrow\u8232 and hit him on his sculpted body armour, \u8232 in the right shoulder. The sharp arrow went in there,\u8232 kept going, and splattered blood down on the curving metal.\'a0  \'97[100]\u8232 At this Lycaon\'92s noble son gave out a noisy shout:\
\'93Come on, you brave horse-lashing Trojans.\uc0\u8232 For the finest of Achaeans has been hurt.\u8232 I don\'92t think he\'92ll long survive my arrow\'92s force,\u8232 if Apollo, son of Zeus, really was the one\u8232 who put it in my heart to leave Lycia.\'94\
That\'92s what Lycaon\'92s son cried out, boasting aloud.But his sharp arrow hadn\'92t killed Diomedes,\uc0\u8232 who moved back to stand beside his chariot and horses.\u8232 He called to Sthenelus, son of Capaneus.\
\'93My friend, son of Capaneus, come on,\uc0\u8232 get down from the chariot, so you can pull  \'97[110]\u8232 this sharp arrow from my shoulder for me.\'94\
Diomedes spoke. Sthenelus jumped down on the ground.\uc0\u8232 Standing beside him, he pulled out the sharp arrow\u8232 stuck in his shoulder. Blood seeped through the woven shirt.\u8232 Diomedes, expert in war cries, then spoke this prayer:\'93Hear me, Athena, unwearied daughter\u8232 of aegis-bearing Zeus. If you\'92ve ever\u8232 loved my father, stood by his side\u8232 in murderous combat, be my friend now.\u8232 Grant that I kill this man, that I come\u8232 a spear\'92s throw from the one who hit me\u8232 unexpectedly and now boasts about it,\u8232 saying I won\'92t see daylight for much longer.\'94\'a0  \'97[120]\
As Diomedes prayed, Pallas Athena heard.\uc0\u8232 She put fresh strength into his legs and upper arms.\u8232 Standing close by, she spoke. Her words had wings.\
\'93Take courage, Diomedes, in this fight with Trojans.\uc0\u8232 I\'92ve put your father\'92s strength into your chest,\u8232 that shield-bearing horseman\'92s fearless power.\u8232 And I\'92ve removed the filter from your eyes\u8232 which covered them before, so now,\u8232 you\'92ll easily distinguish gods from men.\u8232 If a god comes here and stands against you,\u8232 don\'92t offer to fight any deathless one, \'97[130]\u8232 except for Aphrodite, Zeus\'92 daughter.\'a0\u8232 If she fights, cut her with your sharp bronze.\'94\
Bright-eyed Athena left. Diomedes charged off,\uc0\u8232 joining at once those soldiers fighting in the front,\u8232 his spirit on fire to battle Trojans, seized by frenzy\u8232 three times greater than before. He was like a lion\u8232 slightly hurt by a shepherd guarding his sheep flock\u8232 out in the wilds, when it jumps the wall into the pen.\u8232 But he\'92s not killed it. The wound rouses the beast\'92s strength.\u8232 The shepherd can\'92t keep the charging lion from his sheep,\u8232 who, left unguarded, panic. Huddled in a mass,\'a0  \'97[140]\u8232 they crowd in on one another. So the lion,\u8232 in his hot rage, leaps over the wide sheep-fold wall.\u8232 That\'92s how strong Diomedes went to fight the Trojans\u8232 in his angry fury.\'a0\'a0First he killed Astynous,\u8232 and then Hypeiron, a shepherd of his people.\u8232 His bronze spear hit one right above the nipple.\u8232 His huge sword struck the other on the collar,\u8232 by the shoulder, slicing through the shoulder bone,\u8232 severing it from Hypeiron\'92s neck and back.\u8232 He left them there, to chase Abas and Polyidus,\'a0\u8232 sons of old Eurydamas, interpreter of dreams.\'a0  \'97[150]\u8232 The old man didn\'92t visit them to explain their dreams,\u8232 for mighty Diomedes slaughtered both of them.\u8232 Then Diomedes went after Xanthus and Tho\'f6n,\u8232 two sons of Phaenops, both of whom he loved.\u8232 Worn down by sad old age, he\'92d have no other child,\u8232 no person to inherit all his property.\u8232 Diomedes killed them, took the life they loved,\u8232 leaving bitter grief and anguish for their father,\u8232 who wouldn\'92t welcome them back home from war alive.His next of kin thus divided up his assets.\u8232 Diomedes then challenged two sons of Priam,\u8232 son of Dardanus, both in a single chariot\'97 \'97[160]\u8232 Echemmon and Chromius. Just as a lion\u8232 leaps onto cattle and snaps necks on the cows,\u8232 some heifer grazing in the bushes, so Tydeus\'92s son\u8232 knocked them out of their chariot viciously,\u8232 against their will. Then he stripped their armour.\u8232 His companions took the horses to the ships.\
Aeneas saw Diomedes cutting his way\'a0\uc0\u8232 through ranks of soldiers. He charged on through the fight,\u8232 the clash of spears, looking for Pandarus.\u8232 He met Lycaon\'92s son, a fine and powerful man.\u8232 Standing close by, Aeneas said to him:\'a0\'a0\'93Pandarus,  \'97[170]\u8232 where\'92s your bow, your feathered arrows,\u8232 your reputation as a splendid archer?\u8232 No man can match your expertise in that.\u8232 No one in Lycia can claim to be your better.\u8232 Come, raise your hands in prayer to Zeus,\u8232 then shoot an arrow at that man, whose force\u8232 now dominates the field, hurting Trojans badly,\u8232 hacking limbs from many fine young men,\u8232 unless, of course, it is some angry god,\u8232 displeased with Trojans\'92 sacrificial gifts.\u8232 It\'92s hard to stand against a raging god.\'94\
To Aeneas Lycaon\'92s fine son then replied:\'a0\'93Aeneas, counsellor to bronze-armed Trojans,\'a0  \'97[180]\uc0\u8232 from all I see, I think that man must be\u8232 the warlike son of Tydeus. I know him\u8232 by his shield, the visor on his helmet,and by looking at his horses. I\'92m not sure\u8232 he\'92s not a god. But if he\'92s the man\u8232 I think he is, the fierce son of Tydeus,\u8232 he could not be charging at us in this way\u8232 without help from some god beside him,\u8232 an immortal with a covering cloud\u8232 around his shoulders, the god who pushed aside\u8232 that sharp arrow which struck Diomedes.\u8232 For I\'92ve already shot an arrow at him,\u8232 hit his shoulder through that moulded armour.I thought I\'92d shipped him straight to Hades.\'a0  \'97[190]\u8232 But I didn\'92t kill him. The man must be\u8232 some angry god. But we\'92ve no horses here,\u8232 no chariot for me to chase him in.\u8232 In storage in Lycaon\'92s house somewhere\u8232 there are eleven chariots, new ones, too.\u8232 They\'92re beautiful and made just recently,\u8232 but covered up with drapes. Beside each one\u8232 stand pairs of horses, munching wheat and barley.\u8232 When I was coming here, old soldier Lycaon,in his well-built home, gave me much advice.\u8232 He told me to take chariots and horses\u8232 when I lead Trojans into the hot heart of war.\'a0  \'97[200]\u8232 But I didn\'92t follow his advice. If I had,\u8232 things would have been much better for me.\u8232 But I worried about the horses\'97they\'92d lack forage\u8232 with so many men all crammed together,\u8232 and they were used to eating very well.\u8232 I left them and came to Troy to fight on foot,\u8232 relying on my expertise in archery.\'a0\u8232 But that skill is apparently of little use.\u8232 For already I\'92ve hit two of their best men,\u8232 Tydeus\'92 son and the son of Atreus.\u8232 I\'92ve drawn blood from both of them, it\'92s true,\u8232 but that just made them much more dangerous.\u8232 It was a evil time, that day I took  \'97[210]\u8232 my curved bow off its peg to lead my Lycians\u8232 to lovely Troy, a favour for prince Hector.\u8232 If I get home and see with my own eyes\u8232 my native land, my wife, my large and lofty home,\'a0\u8232 let someone chop my head off on the spot,\u8232 if I don\'92t smash this bow with my own hands\u8232 and throw the pieces in the blazing fire.\u8232 For me it\'92s been completely useless.\'94\
Aeneas, leader of the Trojans, then replied:\
\'93Don\'92t talk like that. Things won\'92t change at all\uc0\u8232 until the two of us go out to challenge\u8232 Diomedes with a chariot and horses,\u8232 until we confront him with our weapons. \'97[220]\u8232 Come, get in my chariot. Then you\'92ll see\u8232 how good these horses are from Tros\'92 stock,\u8232 skilled in rapid movement on the plain,\u8232 in all directions, in pursuit or in retreat.\u8232 This pair will take us safely to the city,\u8232 should Zeus give victory to Diomedes.\u8232 Let\'92s go. Take the whip and glistening reins.\u8232 I\'92ll leave you the horses, so I can fight.\u8232 Or if you fight him, I\'92ll control the horses.\'94\
Lycaon\'92s fine son then said in reply:\'a0\'93Aeneas, you should take the reins yourself,  \'97[230]\uc0\u8232 guide your own horses\'97for they will pull\u8232 your curving chariot that much better\u8232 with a driver they\'92re accustomed to,\u8232 if we must flee Tydeus\'92 son this time.\u8232 If they miss your voice, they may shy or panic,\u8232 or refuse to charge straight into battle.\u8232 Then the son of great-hearted Tydeus\u8232 in his attack may kill us both, and lead\u8232 these swift horses off. You drive the chariot,\u8232 guide your horses. I\'92ll do battle with him\'97my spear will give him a sharp welcome.\'94\
They finished talking, climbed up together, and set off,\uc0\u8232 riding out in a fine chariot, both keen to kill,\u8232 driving the swift horses against Tydeus\'92 son. \'97[240]\u8232 Seeing them coming, Sthenelus, Capaneus\'92 brave son,\u8232 at once spoke up to Diomedes\'97his words had wings.\
\'93Diomedes, son of Tydeus, my heart\'92s\uc0\u8232 true friend, I see two men approaching,\u8232 eager to attack you, two powerful men,\u8232 an outstanding team. One\'92s Pandarus,the skilful archer, who boasts he\'92s Lycaon\'92s son.\u8232 The other is Aeneas, proud Anchises\'92 son,\u8232 that\'92s his claim. His mother\'92s Aphrodite.\u8232 So come, let\'92s retire with the horses,\u8232 in case our quick charge through front lines\u8232 ends up costing you your precious life.\'94  \'97[250]\
Strong Diomedes, with a scowl, answered Sthenelus:\
\'93Don\'92t talk of moving back. For I know well\uc0\u8232 you won\'92t persuade me. By birth it\'92s not in me\u8232 to shirk war or seek refuge. My spirit\'92s strong.Nor am I keen to climb up in the chariot.\u8232 I\'92ll go to fight them as I am, on foot.\u8232 Pallas Athena does not allow me\u8232 to withdraw in fear. Their horses may be fast,\u8232 but they\'92ll not carry them both back again,\u8232 away from us, even if one escapes.\u8232 But I will tell you this\'97keep it in mind\'97\u8232 if Athena, that clever schemer, gives me\'a0  \'97[260]\u8232 great glory and I do kill them both,\u8232 then you must hold our swift horses here,\'a0\u8232 tying these reins up to the chariot rail.\u8232 Remember to run down Aeneas\'92 team,\u8232 then drive those horses from the Trojans\u8232 to well-armed Achaeans. For those horses\u8232 come from the stock that wide-seeing Zeus\u8232 gave Tros, payment for Ganymede, his son.*\u8232 They\'92re the finest horses under the sun,\u8232 beneath the light of day. Anchises,\u8232 king of men, got some of that line by stealth,\u8232 putting his mares into Laomedon\'92s herd\u8232 without his knowledge. Six of those horses  \'97[270]\u8232 became the breeding stock on his estate.\u8232 He kept four of them in his own stable\u8232 and gave Aeneas two, horses so fierce,\u8232 they scatter men before them. If we can,\u8232 we\'92ll catch these two, win ourselves great glory.\'94\
As they talked to each other of their strategy,\uc0\u8232 the fast horses quickly brought the two men closer.\u8232 Lycaon\'92s worthy son spoke first, shouting out:\'a0\'93Great spirited, warlike son of Tydeus,\u8232 that noble man, I see that my sharp arrow,\u8232 a bitter shaft, did not destroy you.\u8232 So now I\'92ll try to hit you with my spear.\'94\
He spoke, balanced his long-shadowed spear, and threw it.  \'97[280]\uc0\u8232 The spear hit the son of Tydeus on his shield.\u8232 The bronze point pierced it, but stopped at the body armour.\u8232 Seeing that, Lycaon\'92s fine son let out a mighty cheer:\
\'93You\'92re hit, right in the ribs. You won\'92t last long.\uc0\u8232 I think you\'92ve given me a glorious triumph.\'94\
Unperturbed, powerful Diomedes said to him:\'93You\'92re wrong. You haven\'92t hit me. In my view,\uc0\u8232 this matter won\'92t end for the two of you,\u8232 until one of you falls dead, and his blood\u8232 satisfies in full hard warlike Ares.\'94\
That said, he threw his spear. Athena guided it  \'97[290]\uc0\u8232 straight to Pandarus\'92 nose, directly by the eyes.\u8232 It smashed through his white teeth. The tireless bronze\u8232 sliced through his tongue at its root, coming out his chin,\u8232 right at the tip. Pandarus fell from the chariot,\u8232 his brightly shining armour rattling round him.The swiftly running horses swerved aside.\u8232 Then and there his life-force, his spirit, left him.\u8232 Aeneas then leapt down with his long spear and shield,\u8232 fearing Achaeans would somehow haul away the corpse.\u8232 He made a stand by Pandarus, like a lion,\u8232 confident of its strength. He held his spear in front,\u8232 his round shield, too, with fearful shouts, fiercely eager \'97[300]\u8232 to kill anyone who came up to confront him.\u8232 The son of Tydeus picked up a stone, a massive rock\u8232 which no two men now alive could lift. He threw it\'a0\u8232 all by himself with ease. It hit Aeneas\'92 hip,\u8232 where thigh meets pelvis, what people call the hip joint.\u8232 The boulder smashed the socket and both tendons round it.\u8232 The rough edges on the rock scraped off his skin.\u8232 Falling to his knees, warlike Aeneas stayed down,\u8232 supporting himself with his strong hand on the ground.\u8232 Black night came down and covered both his eyes.  \'97[310]\u8232 Aeneas, king of men, would have perished there,\u8232 if Aphrodite, Zeus\'92 daughter, hadn\'92t seen him right away.\u8232 She was his mother\'97she\'92d conceived him with Anchises,\'a0\u8232 while he was tending cattle. Wrapping her white arms\u8232 around the son she loved, she hid him in the folds\u8232 of her bright gown, to ward off any spears,\u8232 should some Danaan driving with swift horses\u8232 hurl a spear into his chest and take his life.\u8232 She then began to carry her dear son from the fight.\
Meanwhile, Sthenelus, son of Capaneus,\uc0\u8232 did not forget what Diomedes, skilled in war cries,  \'97[320]\u8232 told him. He pulled his sure-footed horses to one side,\u8232 beyond the fight, tying the reins onto the rail,\u8232 and then went after those fine-maned horses of Aeneas.\u8232 He drove the animals away from Trojan lines\u8232 towards well-armed Achaeans. There he gave them\u8232 to his dear companion De\'efpylus, whom he esteemed\u8232 above all others the same age as himself,\u8232 since they both thought alike. He instructed him\u8232 to take them to the hollow ships. Then brave Sthenelus\u8232 climbed back into his chariot, grabbed the shining reins,\u8232 and raced the strong horses back, keen to rejoin Diomedes.\
But Diomedes with his ruthless bronze had gone\'a0  \'97[330]\uc0\u8232 to run down Aphrodite\'97knowing she was not a god\u8232 who could do much in battle, not one of those\u8232 who control men\'92s wars. She was no Athena,\u8232 no goddess Strife, who destroys whole cities.\u8232 He chased her through the crowded battle zone.\u8232 When he met her, great-hearted Tydeus\'92 son\u8232 charged, lunging with his sharp spear at Aphrodite.\u8232 His weapon wounded her slim wrist, piercing the skin\u8232 above her hand, right through her godlike robe,\u8232 a garment the Graces had made for her themselves.*Immortal divine fluid then flowed out, ichor,\u8232 which circulates only in the blessed gods.  \'97[340]\u8232 They don\'92t eat food or drink down gleaming wine.\u8232 Hence, they lack blood, and men call them immortal.\u8232 Aphrodite screamed wildly and let go of her son.\u8232 But Phoebus Apollo caught him in his hands,\u8232 then shielded him with a dark cloud, just in case\u8232 some fast-riding Danaan threw a spear into his chest\u8232 and took away his life. Then Diomedes,\u8232 expert in war cries, shouted loudly:\'93Daughter of Zeus,leave war and fights alone. Isn\'92t it enough\u8232 for you to fool around with feeble women?\u8232 If you start loitering on the battlefield,  \'97[350]\u8232 I think the war will make you shake with terror,\u8232 even though you learn about it from a distance.\'94\
Diomedes spoke. Aphrodite left in agony,\uc0\u8232 distressed and fearful. Wind-swift Iris came to her,\u8232 led her off, out of the crowd, moaning in pain,\u8232 her fair skin stained and wounded. She came across\u8232 fierce Ares, seated on the left flank of the fight,his spear and his fast horses resting on a cloud.\u8232 Falling on her knees, she implored her dear brother,\u8232 pleading hard for his golden-bridled horses:\
\'93Dear brother, save me. Give me your horses,\uc0\u8232 so I may go back up to Mount Olympus,\u8232 the immortals\'92 home. My wound pains me a lot.\'a0  \'97[360]\u8232 A mortal man inflicted this wound on me,\u8232 Tydeus\'92 son, who\'92d now fight Father Zeus himself.\'94\
At this, Ares gave her his golden-bridled horses.\uc0\u8232 She climbed up in the chariot, her fond heart suffering.\'a0\u8232 Getting in beside her, Iris picked up the reins,\u8232 then lashed the horses forward. They flew on willingly.\u8232 At once they reached the gods\'92 home, steep Olympus.\u8232 There wind-swift Iris stopped the horses, untied them\u8232 from the chariot, and gave them heavenly fodder.\u8232 Aphrodite threw herself into her mother\'92s lap,  \'97[370]\u8232 divine Dione, who took her daughter in her arms,\u8232 caressed her with her hand, then said:\'a0\'93My dear child,\u8232 which of the heavenly gods has done this,\u8232 acted so brazenly against you, as if\u8232 you\'92d done something evil in broad daylight?\'94\
Laughter-loving Aphrodite answered her:\
\'93Proud Diomedes, son of Tydeus,\uc0\u8232 wounded me, for I was carrying off\u8232 Aeneas, my dear son, away from battle.\u8232 Of all men, he\'92s the one I love the most.\u8232 Now grim war is not just Trojans and Achaeans,\u8232 for Danaans fight against immortals, too.\'94 \'97[380]\
