With these words, she roused each man\'92s heart and spirit.\uc0\u8232 Bright-eyed Athena quickly moved to Diomedes.\u8232 She found that king beside his chariot and horses,\u8232 recovering from the wound from Pandarus\'92 arrow.\u8232 The sweat under the wide strap of his round shield\'a0\u8232 was bothering him. The chafing made his arms grow tired.\u8232 He was lifting up the strap, wiping off dark blood.\u8232 Setting her hand on the chariot yoke, the goddess said:\'a0\'93Tydeus had a son not much like his father.\'a0  \'97[800]\u8232 He may have been short, but he was a fighter.\u8232 When I would not allow him into battle\u8232 or to display himself, that time he came\u8232 to Thebes alone, far from his Achaeans,\u8232 in the middle of all those Cadmeans,\u8232 I told him to be quiet at the palace feast.\'a0\u8232 But he possessed a powerful spirit\u8232 always active in him. So he challenged\u8232 Cadmean young men and beat them easily.\u8232 That\'92s how much I helped him. Now I stand here,\u8232 beside you, taking care of you, your friend.\u8232 And I\'92m telling you to fight the Trojans. \'97[810]\u8232 But you\'92re either weary after so much action,\u8232 your limbs worn out, or fear has made you timid.\u8232 If so, then you\'92re no son of Tydeus,\u8232 the son of warlike Oeneus.\'94In answer to Athena, mighty Diomedes said:\
\'93I recognize you, goddess daughter\uc0\u8232 of aegis-bearing Zeus. I\'92ll speak to you\u8232 quite openly, concealing nothing. It\'92s not\u8232 that fear has made me hesitant or anxious.\u8232 But I\'92m remembering your own instructions,\u8232 what you laid down. You told me not to fight\u8232 face to face with any immortal god,\u8232 unless Zeus\'92 daughter Aphrodite  \'97[820]\u8232 should come to battle. With my sharp bronze,\'a0\u8232 I was to wound her. I\'92ve pulled myself back,\u8232 and told the other Argives to stay here\u8232 since I see Ares dominates the fight.\'94\
