Saying this, Athena grabbed Sthenelus\'92 hand\uc0\u8232 and hauled him from the chariot to the ground.\u8232 He jumped up at once. The goddess climbed up eagerly\u8232 beside lord Diomedes in the chariot.\u8232 The oaken axle groaned aloud, weighed down,\'a0\u8232 bearing the fearful goddess and the finest man.\u8232 Pallas Athena took up the reins and whip. \'97[840]\u8232 First, she led the sure-footed horses against Ares.\u8232 He was removing armour from huge Periphas,\u8232 Ochesius\'92 fine son, by far the best of the Aetolians.\u8232 Blood-stained Ares was stripping him of all his weapons.\u8232 Then Athena put Hades\'92 helmet on her head,\u8232 so she was invisible to mighty Ares.\u8232 But man-killing Ares did see Diomedes.\u8232 He let the body of huge Periphas lie there,\u8232 where he\'92d first killed him and ripped out his spirit.\u8232 He strode straight up to horse-taming Diomedes.\u8232 When the two came to close quarters and faced each other, \'97[850]\u8232 Ares thrust his bronze spear first, over the yoke\u8232 and horses\'92 reins, eager to take Diomedes\'92 life.\u8232 Athena, bright-eyed goddess, hands gripping the reins,\u8232 shoved the spear aside, so its thrust was harmless,\u8232 above the chariot. Diomedes, skilled in war cries,\u8232 then made the second thrust with his bronze spear.\u8232 Pallas Athena guided the weapon right to Ares\'92 gut,\'a0\u8232 the lower part where his waist band went around him.\u8232 Diomedes wounded Ares, piercing his fair skin,\u8232 then pulled back on his spear. Brazen Ares roared\u8232 as loud as the screams of nine or ten thousand men \'97[860]\u8232 when they clash in war. Fear seized Achaeans\'97Trojans, too.\u8232 They shuddered. That\'92s how strong that cry sounded\u8232 as it came from Ares, insatiable for war.\u8232 Just as a dark mist moves upward from the clouds,\u8232 when in hot weather a strong wind arises,\u8232 so brazen Ares looked to Tydeus\'92 son, Diomedes,\u8232 as the god at once soared up into the clouds,\u8232 ascending to wide heaven. Ares, in a rush,\u8232 went to the gods\'92 home, steep Olympus, sat by Zeus,\u8232 distressed at heart. He showed Zeus where he\'92d been wounded, \'97[870]\u8232 dripping with immortal blood, then made his complaint.\u8232 His words had wings.\'a0 \'93Father Zeus,\u8232 aren\'92t you incensed at this barbarity?\u8232 We gods are always suffering dreadfully\u8232 at each other\'92s hands, when we bring men help.\u8232 We all lay the blame for this on you.\'a0\'a00\u8232 For you gave birth to that insane young girl,\u8232 your destructive daughter, always busy\u8232 with some nastiness. All the other gods,\u8232 all those on Mount Olympus, do what you say.\u8232 And each of us is subject to your will.\u8232 But you never punish her in word or deed.\u8232 You do nothing, because you gave birth to her\u8232 yourself, to Athena, your vicious daughter.*  \'97[880]\u8232 Just now she urged proud Diomedes,\u8232 son of Tydeus, to charge insanely0\u8232 against deathless gods. First he attacked\u8232 Aphrodite and struck her on the wrist.\u8232 Then he charged me, even me, like a god.\u8232 But my quick feet took me away. If not,\u8232 I\'92d be in lasting pain with the fearful dead,\u8232 or have barely lived, wounded by bronze spears.\'94\
